<DOC><DOCNO> AP890908-0088 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-89 1218EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-FlightProblems     09-08 0202</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Flight Problems,0208</SECOND><HEAD>Defense Chief Can't Get off the Ground, Again</HEAD><DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos' streakof aviation bad luck continued Friday when a helicopter sent tofetch him developed engine trouble and made an emergency landingsoutheast of Manila.   An air force spokesman said the helicopter made the unscheduledlanding after the pilot reported unusual vibrations en route toLaguna province, where Ramos was visiting.   Ramos' bad luck with aircraft has become almost legendary in thePhilippines.   In December 1988, his Fokker plane caught fire and burned afterlanding on Samar island. There were no injuries.   A helicopter sent to pick up Ramos the next day crashed into thesea. The four crewmen were rescued.   In February, Ramos was stranded for hours at the U.S.-run SubicBay naval base after his pilot noticed engine trouble beforingtaking off.   Two helicopters sent to pick up Ramos also developed enginetrouble en route to Subic and were forced to turn back to Manila.   In March, Ramos spent his 61st birthday stranded in a ruralmilitary camp near Tacloban after the rotar blade on one of hishelicopters stalled. The aircraft plunged 800 feet before the pilotregained control.</TEXT></DOC>